AB  - We model the bidding for a government contract in which there is imperfect competition; each bidder is better informed about his own costs than either his rival bidders or the government; and the distribution of the domestic firms' costs differs from the distribution of foreign firms' costs because of comparative-advantage effects. We find that the government minimizes its expected procurement cost by operating a price-preference policy, not necessarily purchasing from the lowest bidder.
